  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The user reports the choke plate can be manually closed. This indicates the choke plate itself is not seized. However, for a proper cold start, the automatic choke mechanism must not only close the choke plate but also engage the fast idle cam to increase engine speed and prevent stalling. If the choke plate closes but the engine still won't fire, the fast idle cam may not be engaging, or the choke is opening too quickly, leading to a lean condition during cranking. The next step is to observe the choke plate and fast idle cam during a cold start attempt to determine if the choke is staying closed and if the fast idle is set.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "You state the choke plate closes fully or nearly fully when you manually operate it. This indicates the choke plate itself isn't stuck. However, for a cold start, the fast idle cam must also engage to provide a higher idle speed, preventing the engine from stalling when the choke is active. Without the fast idle, even a properly choked engine can stumble and die. With the engine completely cold, before attempting to start:\n1. Remove the air cleaner.\n2. Manually push the throttle linkage once to set the choke. Confirm the choke plate is nearly closed.\n3. Observe the fast idle cam on the side of the carburetor (refer to Fig. 23 in mustang_fsm_part_09_p401-450.pdf, page 6). The fast idle adjusting screw should be resting on the highest step of the cam.\n4. Attempt to start the engine.\n\nWhat do you observe regarding the choke plate and the fast idle cam during the cranking and initial firing attempt?",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
