    },
    {
      "source": "mustang_fsm_part_08_p351-400.pdf",
      "page": 6,
      "context": "RE-27-55 Tester"
    }
  ],
  "diagnostic_reasoning": "The accelerator pump is confirmed to be delivering fuel, eliminating it as the direct cause. A hesitation on initial acceleration, even with a functioning accelerator pump, can still be caused by an overly lean condition or, critically, incorrect ignition timing. The distributor's advance mechanisms (centrifugal and vacuum) are responsible for adjusting timing based on engine speed and load, which is crucial during acceleration. If these are not functioning correctly, the engine will not receive the proper spark advance, leading to a stumble or hesitation. I will now guide the mechanic to check the ignition timing and the operation of the advance mechanisms as per FSM procedures for the Loadomatic distributor.",
  "mechanic_instructions": "Since the accelerator pump is delivering fuel, the next step is to verify ignition timing, specifically the advance mechanisms. An incorrect advance curve will cause hesitation under acceleration. First, check the initial timing. Warm the engine to operating temperature. Connect a timing light and set the engine speed below 550 RPM. The desired timing mark should align with the pointer. If it does not, loosen the distributor hold-down bolt and rotate the distributor until the mark aligns, then tighten the bolt. Refer to Part 8-1, Section 2 for specific timing specifications and the procedure on page 6 of mustang_fsm_part_08_p351-400.pdf. After confirming initial timing, check the operation of the vacuum and centrifugal advance mechanisms. Refer to 'Loadomatic Distributor' on page 17 of mustang_fsm_part_08_p351-400.pdf. You will need a test set to check advance at various RPM and vacuum settings. Pay close attention to the spark advance limits under low and high vacuum, and throughout the RPM range for centrifugal advance, as detailed in the specifications on page 42 of mustang_fsm_part_08_p351-400.pdf for the 289 2-V V-8.",
  "answer_path_prompts": [
    "The initial timing is incorrect, and I was able to adjust it to specification.",
    "The initial timing is correct, but the vacuum advance mechanism is not functioning or providing the specified advance.",
    "The initial timing is correct, but the centrifugal advance mechanism is not functioning or providing the specified advance.",
    "Both initial timing and the vacuum and centrifugal advance mechanisms appear to be functioning correctly and within specifications."
  ],
  "requires_input": true
}

